  "content": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "What is Z-Index?"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "The z-index property controls the vertical stacking order of positioned elements (which element appears on top)."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Basic Example"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "css",
      "value": ".box1 {\n  position: absolute;\n  z-index: 1;\n}\n\n.box2 {\n  position: absolute;\n  z-index: 2;\n}"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Higher Value = On Top"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "Elements with higher z-index values appear above elements with lower values."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Position Requirement"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "z-index works only on positioned elements (position: relative, absolute, fixed, sticky)."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "css",
      "value": "div {\n  position: relative;\n  z-index: 10;\n}"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Default Stacking"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "Without z-index, elements stack based on their order in the HTML (later elements appear on top)."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Negative Z-Index"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "css",
      "value": "div {\n  position: relative;\n  z-index: -1;\n}"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Stacking Context"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "A stacking context is formed when an element has a position and z-index, isolating its children from other elements."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Example"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "css",
      "value": ".parent {\n  position: relative;\n  z-index: 1;\n}\n\n.child {\n  position: absolute;\n  z-index: 999;\n}"
    },
